Understanding Lifetimes in Rust

6 steps
Completed

This short tutorial introduces you on how lifetimes work in our Rust code! This helps extend your understanding of the ownership model and the borrow checker and why Rust is mostly memory safe.

Let's start learning!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & tutorial-related questions, join our Discord, to ask your question.

Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Recommended to have finished Speedrun Rust.
  • Recommended to have finished some Rust Basics tutorials.
  • A working Rust installation. For instructions, head to https://rustup.rs/ and follow the platform-specific instructions.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Explain how lifetimes work
  • Understand lifetimes without elisions
  • Effectively write Rust code with lifetimes in mind

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: A Quick Review About The Ownership Model

    If you have read over the following tutorial, Who Owns Who? - A Quick Guide to Rust Ownership, Rust's memory model is based on the idea of owning data, aka, the ownership system or ownership model.

    This means that Rust does not rely on a garbage collector to track and manage memory allocations. Each data is tagged as either owned or borrowed (or referenced). Take a look at the code example below. 

    fn main() {
    // Transferring ownership
    let x = String::new();
    let y = x;  // Ownership is transferred to `y`
    println!("{}", x);  // Comment this line to let this code compile.
    println!("{}", y);

    // Borrowing a reference
    let z = String::new();
    let a = &z;
    println!("{}", z);
    println!("a: {}", a);
}
    Rust

    This code won't compile as shown by a screenshot of the compile error below until you comment line 5.

    As you notice, x has owned string data. But on the next line, ownership of the data is transferred to y. This means that x is now dropped and becomes non-existent, thus causing the compile error.

    In the case of borrowing a reference, the variable z still exists since its data is borrowed by the variable a. This memory management is better illustrated in the following diagram if y also has borrowed x as a reference.

    However, this behaviour in managing memory has a hidden feature that was not previously mentioned the concept of lifetimes.

  • Step 2: A First Look At Lifetimes

    In chapter 10.3 of the official Rust documentation, lifetimes are part of the borrow checker. They help tell the compiler that a data is valid before it gets dropped throughout the duration or some duration of program execution, and also within the scope of the execution.

    This way, this ensures memory safety by making sure references do not outlive the data they point to.

    Most of the time, the compiler already knows when data will end or if there is a need to cause a compilation error e.g. dangling references.

    Let's take a look at the following code example and read the comments

    fn main() {
    // First example
    let r;  // A variable with no initial value

    {
        let x = 12;  // A variable within a block statement
        r = x;  // Transferring ownership. Variable x is dropped here.
    }  // r now has ownership of the data

    println!("{}", r);  // You can still print r

    // Second example
    let r;  // Reinitialising a variable of the same name with no initial value

    {
        let x = String::from("A string");  // A variable within a block statement
        r = &x;  // Borrowing instead of transferring ownership
    }  // variable `x` is dropped here

    println!("{}", r);  // You cannot print r here since it points to a dangling reference
}
    Rust

    The first example works because there is a transfer of ownership, the compiler knows that the value of x in the first example has transferred ownership to the variable r. This means, r now owns the data and is not pointing to a reference.

    The second example does not work because the value of x was borrowed as a reference of data. Since block statements have their own local scope, this means x only exists within the block statement. Once the block statement ends, the data associated with x and x itself are dropped.

    Therefore, the last print statement won't print the variable r because it is now pointing to a dangling reference a reference to a non-existing value or data. The error message explains why the code does not compile.

    The "borrowed value does not live long enough" because it is dropped within its own local scope, the block statement.

    The only solution to fix this error is to copy or clone the value.

    But back again to the question, why are lifetimes hidden and can we even explicitly define lifetimes? In the next step, we will discuss how and when to annotate lifetimes.

  • Step 3: A First Look At Lifetimes (Continued)

    The borrow checker in Rust handles references at the start of its creation. The Rust compiler tracks and compares references to the data it is referenced and ensures that the lifetimes of the data lives long enough before it is invalidated. This process is what we refer to as reference validation and is handled by the borrow checker.

    But the Rust compiler cannot infer them all correctly, and sometimes, there is a need to explicitly define lifetimes using lifetime annotations. For example, take a look at this common example.

    fn main() {
    let string_a = String::from("This is a string");
    let result;
    {
        let string_b = String::from("This is also a string");
        result = longest_string(&string_a, &string_b);
    }
    println!("The longest string is `{}`", result);
}

fn longest_string(string_a: &str, string_b: &str) -> &str {
    if string_a.len() > string_b.len() {
        string_a
    } else {
        string_b
    }
}
    Rust

    This code won't compile as shown by the screenshot below.

    The error message implies that the function requires lifetime parameters. Therefore, there is a need to annotate lifetimes to help the compiler understand the lifetimes of passed input data and output data.

    To add lifetime annotations, you must add a single quote followed by the name of the lifetime, usually by a lowercase letter such as from a to z. See the example below with the added lifetime parameter, 'a.

    fn main() {
    let string_a = String::from("This is a string");
    let result;
    {
        let string_b = String::from("This is also a string");
        result = longest_string(&string_a, &string_b);
    }
    println!("The longest string is `{}`", result);
}

fn longest_string<'a>(string_a: &'a str, string_b: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    if string_a.len() > string_b.len() {
        string_a
    } else {
        string_b
    }
}
    Rust

    But this code still does not compile.

    That is because the duration of a lifetime is based on the shortest lifetime of some variable or function or data. In this case, the shortest lifetime would be the variable string_b. As compared to string_a, string_b only lives within its own block and gets dropped once it is out of scope before even reaching the print statement, whereas the lifetime of string_a reaches the end of the main function. This inherently also makes the lifetime of string_b the lifetime of the function longest.

    To fix the code, you can either move string_b out of the block statement, 

    fn main() {
    let string_a = String::from("This is a string");
    let result;
    let string_b = String::from("This is also a string");
    {
        result = longest_string(&string_a, &string_b);
    }
    println!("The longest string is `{}`", result);
}

fn longest_string<'a>(string_a: &'a str, string_b: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    if string_a.len() > string_b.len() {
        string_a
    } else {
        string_b
    }
}
    Rust

    or modify the function to return ownable data e.g. String instead of &str, thus, transfers ownership to the result variable.

    fn main() {
    let string_a = String::from("This is a string");
    let result;
    {
        let string_b = String::from("This is also a string");
        result = longest_string(&string_a, &string_b);
    }
    println!("The longest string is `{}`", result);
}

fn longest_string<'a>(string_a: &'a str, string_b: &'a str) -> String {
    if string_a.len() > string_b.len() {
        string_a.to_string()
    } else {
        string_b.to_string()
    }
}
    Rust

    Both of the two previous code examples compile.

  • Step 4: Lifetime Elisions

    It was mentioned before that the Rust compiler already can infer lifetimes. You don't necessarily have to annotate lifetimes unless the compiler cannot infer them.

    For example, take a look at the following example taken from the previous step.

    fn main() {
    let string_a = String::from("This is a string");
    let result;
    {
        let string_b = String::from("This is also a string");
        result = longest_string(&string_a, &string_b);
    }
    println!("The longest string is `{}`", result);
}

fn longest_string<'a>(string_a: &'a str, string_b: &'a str) -> String {
    if string_a.len() > string_b.len() {
        string_a.to_string()
    } else {
        string_b.to_string()
    }
}
    Rust

    You can change this code to the following code example.

    fn main() {
    let string_a = String::from("This is a string");
    let result;
    {
        let string_b = String::from("This is also a string");
        result = longest_string(&string_a, &string_b);
    }
    println!("The longest string is `{}`", result);
}

fn longest_string(string_a: &str, string_b: &str) -> String {
    if string_a.len() > string_b.len() {
        string_a.to_string()
    } else {
        string_b.to_string()
    }
}
    Rust

    The code will still compile without issues. This is possible because the compiler can "guess" that the references are not needed since the return type is ownable. The lifetimes still exist but elided and annotating them is not needed as the compiler can already infer them.

    Another case is lifetimes in variable scope. This is always elided as there is no need to annotate as it is understandable that the lifetime of a variable depends if the data is either a reference or owned data. See code example below for more info and read the comments.

    fn main() {
    let x = String::from("A string"); // Note that this type only implements clone
    let y = x; // Ownership moves here
    let z = &y; // Lifetime of z is the same as lifetime of y
    let a = &z; // Lifetime of a is the same as lifetime of z

    println!("{}", a);
    println!("{}", y);
    println!("{}", z);

    let i; // Initialised a variable with no value.

    {
        let b = &a; // Lifetime of b is dependent on the scope.
        println!("{}", b);
        i = &b;  // Dangling reference after b is dropped.
    } // `b` is dropped here. `a` still exists as a reference since it is
      // outside of the block statement
    println!("{}", a);
    println!("{}", i);  // Comment this out to make the code compile since `b`
                        // at this point becomes a dangling reference.
}
    Rust
  • Step 5: Static Lifetimes

    Rust has the concept of static lifetimes. The lifetimes of these data have a special lifetime specifier or parameter called 'static.

    The lifetimes of this data exist for the entire duration of the program. It can still be coerced to a shorter lifetime, for example, if it's within a block statement or another function that has a shorter scope.

    They exist as either constants or string literals. Both are stored as read-only memory of the binary.

    static HELLO: &str = "HELLO";
const NUM: i32 = 0;
    Rust

    Rust has two different types of constants. An unchangeable value called using the const keyword and a possibly mutable variable using the static keyword. See the code example below for more info and read the code comments.

    static mut NUM: i32 = 10; // This can either be immutable or mutable
const ANOTHER_NUM: i32 = 12; // Constants are always immutable
static ACTS_LIKE_CONSTANT: i32 = 10; // Immutable static are similar to constants

fn main() {
    let y: &'static str = "World";
    let h;
    {
        let s: &'static str = "Hello";
        h = &s; // Lifetime is still shorter and follow scoping rules
    } // `s` is dropped here
    println!("{}", h); // Comment this out to make this code compile.
    unsafe {
        NUM = NUM + 2;
    }; // Mutating static but mutable variables is an unsafe operation.

    #[allow(static_mut_refs)]  // Requires a compiler attribute to be here as it is denied by default
    unsafe {
        println!("NUM: {} | ANOTHER_NUM: {}", NUM, ANOTHER_NUM);
    } // Using a static but mutable variables is an unsafe operation.
    let total = ANOTHER_NUM + ACTS_LIKE_CONSTANT;
    println!("{} + {} = {}", ANOTHER_NUM, ACTS_LIKE_CONSTANT, total);
}
    Rust
  • Step 6: Stacking It Up!

    Congratulations on finishing this tutorial! You have gained basic knowledge about lifetimes in Rust and how they make Rust memory safety possible!
